routing_summary.excerpt_summary: Section 11 defines the IANA-related actions for TLS 1.3 (cipher suites, content types, alerts, handshake types, extensions, certificate types/status, supported groups, and the new SignatureScheme and PskKeyExchangeMode registries), plus meta‑instructions to update RFC 8446 references and rename the extended_main_secret extension.

Temporal.explanation: Purely registry/administrative text; no sequencing, timers, or state transitions.

ActorDirectionality.explanation: Only refers to IANA’s role in maintaining registries, no protocol message flow.

Scope.explanation: Scope of rules (per registry) is clear and matches the registries’ intended use.

Causal.explanation: No operational algorithm here; registry policies do not drive protocol behavior directly.

Quantitative.explanation: Byte ranges for codepoints and registry ranges are consistent with referenced RFCs; no size/range math to reconcile.

Deontic.explanation: Normative language (“MUST”, “assigned via Specification Required”, etc.) is consistent with BCP 26 and prior TLS IANA texts; no conflicting requirements detected.

Structural.explanation: Registry names and fields (e.g., TLS Cipher Suites, TLS ExtensionType Values, TLS SignatureScheme) match existing IANA structures; field mappings to appendices (B.2, B.3, B.4) are coherent.

CrossRFC.explanation: Policies (Specification Required, Private Use), column semantics (“Recommended”, “DTLS‑OK”), and specific updates (e.g., ocsp_multi_RESERVED, OpenPGP_RESERVED, x25519/x448 references) align with RFC 4346, 4366, 6091, 6961, 7919, 8126, 8422, 8446, and 8447 as excerpted.

Terminology.explanation: Terminology for registries and entries (e.g., “extended_main_secret”, “general_error”, “TLS PskKeyExchangeMode”) is consistent and unambiguous.

Boundary.explanation: No edge‑case behaviors are defined here; this is about registry ranges and policies already covered by BCP 26 patterns.

candidate_issues.short_label: No substantive specification or registry inconsistency detected in Section 11
candidate_issues.sketch_for_experts: The IANA Considerations in this draft largely restate or minimally extend the IANA policies and contents established by RFC 8446 and RFC 8447, plus the expected new “general_error” alert and renaming of the extended_main_secret extension. All codepoint ranges, allocation policies (Specification Required vs Private Use), “Recommended”/“DTLS‑OK” column rules, and registry names align with the referenced RFCs. Any oddities (e.g., slightly awkward wording in the introductory paragraph, duplication in mentioning general_error, or repeating older name‑normalization steps) are editorial and do not affect protocol behavior or registry correctness.
